div.p:
               After the mail-work, dear Prof. Tate, I commenced this afternoon at once the examination of your plants and finished off so far as to anounce the addition of three plants to the S.A. flora, namely Phyllanthus australis, Lobelia platycalyx and a new species of Nablonium, to which I shall give your honored name.



                     M appears subsequently to have changed his mind about this, since he never published Nablonium Tatei.
                To morrow I will write carefully a diagnosis and forward it to you, so that you can introduce your essay by a new plant. The Grevillea may be a form of G. parviflora, but without flowers that remains doubtful. The Hydrocotyle = H. tripartita; the supposed Choretrum = Leptomeria aphylla; the Myoporum is the typical M. parvifolium and may be distinct from M. humile; — the Patersonia = P. glauca;

The five plant names are each ticked in the margin.
                — the restoid looking pl. = Chorizandra enodis; — Scirpus nodosus = S. inundatus; — Schoenus brevifolius = S. nitens;

This name is marked with a tick above it.
                — the annual grass = Festuca bromoides; — the Distichlis = Sporobolus Virginianus;




                     S. virginicus?
                — the Potamogeton may be distinct from P. natans, but it is not in fruit.
